Package neureka.backend.api

Interface Algorithm<FinalType extends Algorithm<FinalType>>

All Known Implementing Classes:
AbstractBaseAlgorithm, AbstractFunctionalAlgorithm, Activation, Broadcast, Convolution, GenericAlgorithm, GenericAlgorithm, Operator, Scalarization
public interface Algorithm<FinalType extends Algorithm<FinalType>>
This class is the middle layer of the 3 tier abstraction architecture of this backend.
Conceptually an implementation of the Algorithm interface represents "a sub-kind of operation" for an instance of an implementation of the Operation interface.
The "+" operator for example has different Algorithm instances tailored to specific requirements originating from different ExecutionCall instances with unique arguments. Tsr instances within an execution call having the same shape would cause the Operation instance to chose an Algorithm instance which is responsible for performing elementwise operations, whereas otherwise the Broadcast algorithm might be called to perform the operation.

    • setImplementationFor

      <D extends Device<?>,​ E extends ImplementationFor<D>> FinalType setImplementationFor​(java.lang.Class<D> deviceClass, E execution)
      Implementations of the Algorithm interface ought to express a compositional design pattern.
      This means that concrete implementations of an algorithm for a device are not extending an Algorithm, they are components of it instead.
      These components can be stored on an Algorithm by passing a Device class as key and an ImplementationFor instance as value.
